The Chronicle Chronicle Reporter
THE situation in Bulawayo suburbs is calm and streets were largely deserted with most businesses and shops especially in the city centre remaining closed. <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-506152" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/565552F9-1CB7-4709-AA70-BCE70D313E2A.png" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/565552F9-1CB7-4709-AA70-BCE70D313E2A.png 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/565552F9-1CB7-4709-AA70-BCE70D313E2A-360x200.png 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> A Chronicle news visited a number of suburbs and observed that a few people and cars were on the streets. <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-506154" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/EC74C3CB-A734-4E0C-8626-EBBB52E949FE.png" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/EC74C3CB-A734-4E0C-8626-EBBB52E949FE.png 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/EC74C3CB-A734-4E0C-8626-EBBB52E949FE-360x200.png 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" />
Most shops were closed and the presence of law enforcement officers is visible on most street corners in the city centre. In western suburbs, most bus stops were empty and Zupco buses were waiting for passengers. <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-506156" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/5A1B79F6-6C16-414A-AC15-6DB94D586639.png" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/5A1B79F6-6C16-414A-AC15-6DB94D586639.png 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/5A1B79F6-6C16-414A-AC15-6DB94D586639-360x200.png 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" />
A few shops were open in selected areas in Western suburbs. In the eastern suburbs, it was business as usual at shopping centres. <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-506158" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/E6ACE5AF-B9B1-44FB-ABF4-4E9B159CA54F.png" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/E6ACE5AF-B9B1-44FB-ABF4-4E9B159CA54F.png 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/E6ACE5AF-B9B1-44FB-ABF4-4E9B159CA54F-360x200.png 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Although the situation is calm, police and soldiers are continuously monitoring movements of people and vehicles. <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-506163" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/9C85CE53-B8D5-400E-BEA3-716AC3E210EB.png" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/9C85CE53-B8D5-400E-BEA3-716AC3E210EB.png 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/9C85CE53-B8D5-400E-BEA3-716AC3E210EB-360x200.png 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-506160" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/1ADF86CA-3E85-48F8-8A67-A124B80EAFBD.png" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/1ADF86CA-3E85-48F8-8A67-A124B80EAFBD.png 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/1ADF86CA-3E85-48F8-8A67-A124B80EAFBD-360x200.png 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" />